# Wearable Ankle Motion Tracking System

An embedded wearable system for measuring ankle motion using inertial sensing and delivering real-time visual and haptic feedback.

---

## Overview

This project uses an ESP32 and MPU-6050 IMU to capture ankle motion data and convert it into real-time feedback using LEDs and vibration motors.

The system is designed as a foundation for biomechanics applications such as gait analysis and motion tracking.

---

## Key Features

- Reads acceleration and angular velocity using MPU-6050
- Processes motion data using ESP32
- Provides real-time LED and vibration feedback
- Built as a wearable embedded prototype

---

## What I Built

- Interfaced MPU-6050 with ESP32 using I2C communication
- Developed firmware to read and process sensor data
- Implemented LED control using WS2812B LED ring
- Designed vibration feedback system using GPIO output
- Built and tested full system on breadboard

---

## Hardware

- ESP32
- MPU-6050 IMU
- WS2812B LED ring
- Vibration motors
- Breadboard and jumper wires

---

## Software

- Arduino IDE
- C/C++
- Wire library (I2C)
- Adafruit NeoPixel library

---

## System Architecture

MPU-6050 → ESP32 → LED + Vibration Feedback

---

## Current Status

- Sensor communication working
- Firmware in progress
- Hardware prototype built on breadboard

